  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several key ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- These establish global standards and expectations for anti-money laundering (AML) practices\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate to investigate and prosecute cross-border money laundering\n- Sharing intelligence and evidence\n- Extradition of suspects\n- Freezing and seizing international assets\n\n3. Standardized Regulatory Frameworks\n- Consistent definitions of money laundering\n- Similar reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n- Suspicious transaction reporting mechanisms\n\n4. Compliance and Enforcement\n- Countries implement international standards into domestic legislation\n- Regular assessments of national AML frameworks\n- Potential sanctions for non-compliance\n\n5. Information Sharing\n- International financial intelligence units\n- Coordinated tracking of suspicious financial transactions\n- Cross-border communication between law enforcement agencies\n\n6. Technological Adaptations\n- Addressing emerging challenges like cryptocurrency\n- Developing consistent digital financial monitoring approaches\n\nThese intersections create a complex but increasingly coordinated global approach to combating money laundering.",
